*Prepared by Bill Hereth · last updated 2026-07-11*


## The Question

What would it look like, in rough terms, if more people who live in an area of our region also worked in that area — instead of commuting elsewhere? This sketch-level test asks: if a share of home-based-work (HBW) trips that currently start inside a target area but end outside it instead ended inside the target area — following today's existing internal destination pattern — what would change at the corridor and regional level?

Three geography types are tested, each applied region-wide (every area of that type shifted simultaneously): **City Area** (roughly a single incorporated city boundary, ~80 areas region-wide — ~55 in WFRC, ~25 in MAG), **Medium District** (a mid-sized planning district, coarser than city boundaries, often spanning parts of one or more cities or unincorporated areas — ~48 areas region-wide, ~35 WFRC / ~13 MAG), and **Workshop Area** (the same city groupings used for our public workshops — ~12 region-wide, 8 WFRC / 4 MAG). Per the approved scoping memo, **City Area is the lead geography for this write-up**; Medium District and Workshop Area are shown throughout as a robustness check across scales. The model basis is the **2027 RTP adoption year** network and land use, model version **v10.0.0-beta.1**.

This is not a land-use forecast. It is a directional, order-of-magnitude check on whether "closer jobs-housing balance" is worth studying further — see [Caveats](#caveats-and-interpretation).

---

## Plain-Language Takeaways

- At a **10% shift**, **City Area** redistribution reduces region-wide Peak-period vehicle-hours of delay (VHD) by roughly **27,887 hours/day** and Peak-period VMT by roughly **1,160,782 miles/day** — a small fraction of regional totals, but directionally consistent with what the mechanism should produce.
- Peak-period vehicle-hours of travel per household falls by about **3.2 minutes/day** region-wide under the City Area scenario — the closest read on "time given back to households."
- Medium District and Workshop Area shifts produce **similar-direction, somewhat smaller** reductions at this shift level — see the [cross-scale comparison](#cross-scale-comparison).
- **Transit ridership on TRAX, FrontRunner, and bus all decline slightly** under all three geography types — shortening commutes reduces the number of trips long enough for transit to compete on, an important, non-obvious side effect (see [Transit Ridership](#transit-ridership)).

**For funding and capacity-prioritization decisions**, which tend to focus on the Peak period and on corridors already near or over capacity:

- The Peak-period VHD reduction is not spread evenly — it concentrates on the region's already most heavily-traveled, most delay-prone corridors. **I-15** sees the largest single-corridor Peak VHD reduction (**13,893 hours/day**) under the City Area scenario — see [Corridor Detail](#corridor-detail).
- Peak-period **miles of severely congested roadway (V/C > 1.0) fall by about 44.1 miles** region-wide (from **170.3 miles** today) under the City Area scenario — a length-based read on how much less roadway crosses into failing conditions during the commute peaks, distinct from delay/VMT and more directly comparable to how capacity-expansion needs are typically scoped — see [Severe Congestion](#severe-congestion).
- Because the mechanism only touches HBW destinations (not capacity or land use), it doesn't substitute for planned roadway investment — it's a directional read on how much *demand-side* pressure a closer jobs-housing balance could take off the same corridors that funding decisions already target.
- Most charts below let you **toggle between shift levels**, and the VMT/VHD/VHT charts also toggle between **Peak, Off-Peak, and Daily** periods — see [Caveats](#caveats-and-interpretation) before drawing conclusions regardless of level.


---

## How the Test Works {#how-the-test-works}

Home-based-work trips starting inside a target area but ending outside it are identified in the model's trip table. A share of those trips (5%, 10%, or 25%) is proportionally redistributed to end inside the target area instead, following the *existing* internal destination pattern (a location that already attracts 15% of work trips into the area gets 15% of the newly shifted trips too). This redistribution is applied to the HBW destination-choice matrix **before mode choice**; everything downstream (mode choice, assignment) runs normally on the adjusted trip pattern. Everything else about the region — total trips, population, other destinations — is unchanged.

---

## Big Picture: Region-Wide Effect by Shift Level {#big-picture}

The detailed charts below let you toggle between shift levels one at a time. These two are the opposite: every shift level shown **at once**, side by side, region-wide, Peak period only — so the overall size of the effect (and how it scales with shift size) is visible at a glance, without clicking through options.

